steps to taking someone to small claims court i am a contractor a customer owes me a little over after several phone calls i went to her house she said that she will have it in the mail soon for some reason i don't believe it how hard is it to take someone to small claims court or place a lein on their house you go to the courthouse in her district and ask you fill out some forms someone will help you and then pay to have her served neither of you needs a lawyer a court date is set and you present your case be prepared she may counter saying you did sloppy work didn't finish whatever if she doesn't show you may win by default unless she presents the judge with a very good reason for not showing after hearing both sides the judge makes a decision if it's in your favor you will have a judgment against her the problem will be collecting you can turn the judgment over to a collection bureau sell it of try to collect be careful that what you do is legal as a contractor you can even have a claim on her house when if she sells it assumning she owns it Appeal Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Lawsuit SCO-Linux controversies The Apprentice 2 Jury Article One of the United States Constitution Child support Surveillance United States district court Government of Maryland Motion (legal) Tom DeLay Karl Rove United Kingdom corporation tax Schabir Shaik Trial Court system of Canada Fathers' rights Joshua Benjamin Jeyaretnam Lawyer Plame affair GNU General Public License John Roberts Supreme Court of Israel Washington gubernatorial election, 2004 Samuel Alito Stare decisis 2005 trial of Michael Jackson Blackjack Medical malpractice Ruth Bader Ginsburg Poker jargon FairTax Sheriff Terri Schiavo Schapelle Corby Capitalism Hugo Black Arbitration Microeconomics Judgment Judicial functions of the House of Lords Pledge of Allegiance Inter-American Court of Human Rights Concurrent estate Mumia Abu-Jamal U.S. Electoral College Slander and libel Israeli West Bank barri